story: Being an international student is tough. And

, my birthday came and went and I had no one to spend it with. I called my mum and dad that day and tried my best to hide my tears but they knew something was wrong. The call lasted 3 hours. I cried for at least 2/3s of that time. I had no energy left after that and slept like a baby that night.

I was stressed out of my mind for my first round of midterms. My parents drove an hour to Waterloo and dropped off some groceries, which is unusual for me. They didn't expect anything in return, and knew I had to study, so they hugged me and drove an hour back. I broke down in tears and couldn't tell why. Just a subtle reminder that I am so lucky to have my family behind me, and how well they know me.

I had just written my first midterm of university. I felt uneasy and anxious leaving the exam room. As I was walking out and talking with friends none of my answers were matching up. I started having a panic attack and called my mom. She was quick to comment maybe I had chosen the wrong program. I felt hopeless and like I did not deserve to be here.

*Trigger warning: eating disorder* I was dealing with an eating disorder as a result of stress. School and co-op felt out of my control, so the food I was consuming seemed like the only thing I could control - causing
, and

. When I lost weight I thought I would be happy but additional stress from thinking about food consumed my life. I was scared of eating, scared of not working out and scared of how others would perceive me once they found out about my disordered eating, so I isolated myself from social events. I secretly cried in my room almost everyday at Icon. I'm still on the recovery journey and in a much happier place, but often think back to how lonely and unhappy I was, lived so close with friends yet felt so disconnected.

TW: Eating disorders. I spent almost every lunch time in 2nd year in this stairwell while struggling with
. It was small and quiet. Rarely anyone interrupted me. I liked it because it was near the

, so I got to hear my friends talking and laughing and eating together as I passed by to my hiding spot. I wanted so badly to be with them, but I couldn't handle anyone seeing how much I was eating or judging me for it. So I settled with hearing their voices and eating in silence on the nearby stairs. One day, as I picked away at a small, sad salad, the depth of my sadness hit me and I cried.
I was diagnosed with 3 mental illnesses. It was relief to finally know what was happening to me. But also, that this was something I would need to treat and medicate for the rest of my life.

story: My class had a terrible exam. Everyone was confused and thought the content didn't match what we had been taught. And the night after we took it, our professor released the marks to us. I had failed by 1 single point. In the dead of winter, I left my house without a jacket and walked to the edge of the lake. I sat there for a good hour trying to convince myself it was worthwhile to stay alive. It was worth it. I made it home safely that night.
featuredStories.location: The edge of Silver Lake in Waterloo Park

story: I've always struggled with anxiety and loneliness and I'm pretty shy but I decided to try harder to make new friends once first year began. I finally started making friends but after a while everyone drifted off once they found other people who were more interesting, and I found myself alone once again. I was frustrated and I began to wonder if I was the problem all along.
I was studying for a calculus final for the following week, when I got a call from my mom that a relative had just passed away. I felt
that I didn't talk with him much, and wished I could be with my family. Stress about passing that exam didn't help either.

It was the night before my first two big papers of graduate school were due. Everyone else in my cohort had already finished and gone out to celebrate, but I was still trying to finish both my papers. I felt like a waste of space in the program and like I was letting down my supervisor. I was alone and it was dark in the graduate student lounge at the time and I remember just putting my head down on the desk and sobbing. It cleared my head enough to finish though, and I did well on both, so at least it had a happy ending.
After the last night of

, I went to get breakfast at Mel's Diner with fellow orientation leaders. I cried tears of exhaustion and happiness that we helped welcome thousands of first-year students to the University of Waterloo.

My tears were collected during my undergrad in my 4A capstone project midterm update meeting. That meeting showed me that nobody in my Mech Eng, department believed in me or understood how I wanted to express engineering. Luckily, my supervisor, from a different department, did.

I was so overwhelmed with emotion from nothing in particular. Just being so sad for so long and not being able to contain it anymore. I had no control. At least I could control where I was, I chose to run and hide in the big cedar trees by Laurel creek, letting them shield me from others' stares.
featuredStories.location: Hiding in the trees near Laurel Creek

story: Graduation... It should have been a crowning moment for my mental state, but during the ceremony I still felt like such a failure. That day I realized how important it was that I take care of myself. I could not even be happy the day I had diploma in hand with my parents and best friend onlooking. It is the most concerning sensation to be surrounded by happy people, and feel nothing but emptiness inside, and the tears running down your face.
I had just got
for the first time in my life and cried in sadness. My wonderful roommate brought me bubble tea and then I cried out of happiness.
featuredStories.location: Conrad Grebel residence fourth floor short end

story: It was my first day of second year. I had just finished a theatre class (ML building), and felt I was struggling with socializing. I left class and bumped into a friend from high school, but I was so anxious I couldn't talk. I made my way to the Davis Centre got my self some food and sat down. I just started crying uncontrollably - I felt really alone. Some guy came up and checked on me. I felt embarrassed, being a big guy just crying in the middle of a crowd of people, but the stranger didn't shame me, instead calmed me down. That was the first time I cried on campus, in a year that would end with me dropping out.

I was at rock bottom in my 2A term - constantly skipped class to cry in bed because I felt so overwhelmed and alone. Ended up failing 3 classes and got kicked out the program which led me to cry myself to sleep almost every night for a year by telling myself how big of a failure I am. that I love!
